  "text": "The Node.js child_process module implements comprehensive command injection prevention through null-byte validation at multiple layers:\n\n## JavaScript Validation Layer (lib/child_process.js)\n\nThe main entry points (spawn, exec, execFile, fork) use the **normalizeSpawnArguments** function (line 538-709) to validate and normalize all arguments. The function calls **validateArgumentNullCheck** (line 963-967) on critical string parameters, which rejects any string containing the null byte character ('\\u0000'). This validation is applied to:\n\n1. **file** parameter (line 540) - The command/executable path\n2. **args** parameter (line 556) - Via validateArgumentsNullCheck helper (line 970-974) that validates each array element\n3. **options.argv0** parameter (line 597)\n4. **options.shell** parameter (line 613)\n5. **options.env** keys and values (lines 691-692)\n\nThe **exec** function (line 231) uses **normalizeExecArgs** (line 188-206) which calls validateArgumentNullCheck on the command string (line 190).\n\nThe **fork** function (line 122) validates options.execPath (line 142) and execArgv array (line 146).\n\n## Internal ChildProcess Class (lib/internal/child_process.js)\n\nThe **ChildProcess** constructor function (line 254) creates a native Process object via `new Process()` (line 266), which is bound to the C++ ProcessWrap class. The **ChildProcess.prototype.spawn** method (line 354-479) calls `this._handle.spawn(options)` (line 395) to delegate to the C++ binding, which receives already-validated arguments from normalizeSpawnArguments.\n\n## C++ Native Binding Layer\n\n### ProcessWrap Class (src/process_wrap.cc)\n\nThe **ProcessWrap** class (line 51-346) is the C++ binding that wraps the libuv process handle. It implements:\n\n1. **Initialize** method (line 53-69) - Sets up the native constructor and binds methods\n2. **Spawn** method (line 153-310) - The main native spawn implementation that:\n   - Extracts validated arguments from the JavaScript object\n   - Retrieves the file path (line 193-197)\n   - Parses arguments array (line 208-225)\n   - Processes environment variables (line 236-251)\n   - Calls uv_spawn (line 286) to fork the process\n3. **Kill** method (line 312-325) - Sends signals to child processes\n\nThe C++ layer does not need to re-validate for null bytes because the JavaScript validation layer guarantees that all string inputs are null-byte-free before reaching the native code.\n\n### SyncProcessRunner Class (src/spawn_sync.h/cc)\n\nThe **SyncProcessRunner** class handles synchronous spawning (spawnSync, execSync, execFileSync). It provides similar validation and spawning functionality through the **Spawn** static method, parsing options and executing processes synchronously using libuv's synchronous spawning mechanism.\n\n## Defense Mechanism\n\nThe null-byte validation prevents command injection by ensuring that:\n\n1. File paths cannot contain embedded null bytes that could truncate the actual executable path\n2. Arguments cannot contain null bytes that could be interpreted as terminators\n3. Environment variables (both keys and values) cannot contain null bytes\n4. Shell paths and argv0 parameters are validated\n\nThe validation uses `StringPrototypeIncludes(arg, '\\u0000')` (line 964) to check for null bytes and throws ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE if any are found. This is applied consistently across all entry points (spawn, exec, execFile, fork and their sync variants) before any arguments reach the C++ binding layer.\n\nTest coverage is provided in test/parallel/test-child-process-reject-null-bytes.js which validates that null bytes in all parameters are rejected with proper error handling."
}

